{
  "texts": [
    "Similar to the Shapiro-Wilk test, a p-value less than 0.05 suggests that the data are not normally distributed.Explanation of p-values: In this analysis, a p-value < 0.05 was considered to indicate that the data did not follow a normal distribution.",
    "This threshold is the widely accepted standard in statistical research for rejecting the null hypothesis of normality.",
    "A p-value below 0.05 means there is less than a 5% probability that the observed differences between the data distribution and the normal distribution are due to chance, justifying the decision to apply non-parametric tests instead of parametric ones in cases where normality was not met.By including these tests and clarifying the interpretation of p-values and the normality threshold, we provide a solid and transparent basis for statistical evaluation, thereby strengthening the rigor and credibility of the methods and results employed in this study.",
    "F. Statistical Test Results (Mann-Whitney)Since many of the data were not normally distributed, the Mann-Whitney test was used to compare the groups.Table 6 shows that there were no significant differences between the experimental and control groups in terms of coherence, accuracy, originality, depth of content, and problem-solving ability, suggesting that both groups have similar skills in these areas.",
    "However, a significant difference was found in the use of sources, where the experimental group showed lower performance compared to the control group, indicating a need for improved training or instruction in sourcing and managing references in the experimental group."
  ]
}